M|prioritization-advisor|**Q1 rsp:** "Early PMF, scaling — Found initial PMF; growing fast; adding features to retain/expand"
M|prioritization-advisor|**Q2 rsp:** "Cross-functional team, aligned — Product, design, engineering aligned; clear goals"
M|prioritization-advisor|**Q3 rsp:** "Lack of data-driven decisions — Prioritizing by gut feel; want metrics-based process"
M|prioritization-advisor|**Q4 rsp:** "Some data — Basic anl, customer feedback, but no rigorous data collection"
M|prioritization-advisor|**Recommended Framework: RICE (Reach, Impact, Confidence, Effort)**
M|prioritization-advisor|**Why this fits:**
M|prioritization-advisor|- You have some data (anl, customer feedback) to estimate Reach and Impact
M|prioritization-advisor|- Cross-functional team alignment means you can agree on scoring criteria
M|prioritization-advisor|- Transitioning from gut feel to data-driven = RICE provides structure without overwhelming complexity
M|prioritization-advisor|- Early PMF stage = need speed, but also need to prioritize high-impact features for retention/expansion
M|prioritization-advisor|**When to use it:**
M|prioritization-advisor|- Quarterly or monthly roadmap planning
M|prioritization-advisor|- When backlog exceeds 20-30 items
M|prioritization-advisor|- When stakeholders debate priorities
M|prioritization-advisor|**When NOT to use it:**
M|prioritization-advisor|- For strategic, multi-quarter bets (RICE favors incremental wins)
M|prioritization-advisor|- When you lack basic metrics (Reach requires usage data)
M|prioritization-advisor|- For single-feature decisions (overkill)
M|prioritization-advisor|**Implementation:**
M|prioritization-advisor|- **Reach:** How many users will this feature affect per month/quarter?
M|prioritization-advisor|- **Impact:** How much will it improve their experience? (1 = minimal, 2 = high, 3 = massive)
M|prioritization-advisor|- **Confidence:** How confident are you in your Reach/Impact estimates? (50% = low data, 80% = good data, 100% = certain)
M|prioritization-advisor|- **Effort:** How many person-months to build? (Include design, engineering, QA)
M|prioritization-advisor|- Use a spreadsheet or Airtable
M|prioritization-advisor|- Involve PM, design, engineering in scoring (not just PM solo)
M|prioritization-advisor|- Be honest about Confidence (don't inflate scores)
M|prioritization-advisor|- Formula: `(Reach × Impact × Confidence) / Effort`
M|prioritization-advisor|- Higher score = higher priority
M|prioritization-advisor|- Sort by RICE score
M|prioritization-advisor|- rv top 10-20 with stakeholders
M|prioritization-advisor|- Adjust for strategic priorities (RICE doesn't capture everything)
M|prioritization-advisor|**Example Scoring:**
M|prioritization-advisor|| Feature | Reach | Impact | Confidence | Effort | RICE Score |
M|prioritization-advisor||---------|-------|--------|------------|--------|------------|
M|prioritization-advisor|| Email reminders | 5,000 | 2 | 70% | 1 | 7,000 |
M|prioritization-advisor|| Mobile app | 10,000 | 3 | 60% | 6 | 3,000 |
M|prioritization-advisor|| Dark mode | 8,000 | 1 | 90% | 0.5 | 14,400 |
M|prioritization-advisor|**Priority:** Dark mode > Email reminders > Mobile app (despite mobile app having high Reach/Impact, Effort is too high)
M|prioritization-advisor|**Alternative Framework: ICE (Impact, Confidence, Ease)**
M|prioritization-advisor|**Why this might work:**
M|prioritization-advisor|- Simpler than RICE (no Reach calculation)
M|prioritization-advisor|- Faster to score (good if you need quick decisions)
M|prioritization-advisor|**Tradeoffs:**
M|prioritization-advisor|- Less data-driven (no Reach metric = can't compare features affecting different user bases)
M|prioritization-advisor|- More subjective (Impact/Ease are gut-feel, not metrics)
M|prioritization-advisor|**Common Pitfalls:**
M|prioritization-advisor|1. **Overweighting Effort** — Don't avoid hard problems just because they score low. Some strategic bets require high effort.
M|prioritization-advisor|2. **Inflating Confidence** — Be honest. 50% confidence is okay if data is scarce.
M|prioritization-advisor|3. **Ignoring str** — RICE doesn't capture strategic importance. Adjust for vision/goals.
M|prioritization-advisor|**Q1 rsp:** "Pre-product/market fit — Searching for PMF; experimenting rapidly"
M|prioritization-advisor|**Q2 rsp:** "Small team, limited resources — 3 engineers, 1 PM"
M|prioritization-advisor|**Q3 rsp:** "Too many ideas, unclear which to pursue"
M|prioritization-advisor|**Q4 rsp:** "Minimal data — New product, no usage metrics"
M|prioritization-advisor|**Recommended Framework: ICE (Impact, Confidence, Ease) or Value/Effort Matrix**
M|prioritization-advisor|**Why NOT RICE:**
M|prioritization-advisor|- You don't have usage data to estimate Reach
M|prioritization-advisor|- Pre-PMF = you need speed, not rigorous scoring
M|prioritization-advisor|- Small team = overhead of RICE scoring is too heavy
M|prioritization-advisor|**Why ICE instead:**
M|prioritization-advisor|- Lightweight, gut-check framework
M|prioritization-advisor|- Can score 20 ideas in 30 minutes
M|prioritization-advisor|- Good for rapid experimentation phase
M|prioritization-advisor|**Or Value/Effort Matrix:**
M|prioritization-advisor|- Visual 2x2 matrix (high value/low effort = quick wins)
M|prioritization-advisor|- Even faster than ICE
M|prioritization-advisor|- Good for stakeholder alignment (visual, intuitive)
M|prioritization-advisor|**Symptom:** Pre-PMF startup using weighted scoring with 10 criteria
M|prioritization-advisor|**Consequence:** Overhead kills speed. You need experiments, not rigorous scoring.
M|prioritization-advisor|**Fix:** Match framework to stage. Pre-PMF = ICE or Value/Effort. Scaling = RICE. Mature = Opportunity Scoring or Kano.
M|prioritization-advisor|**Symptom:** Switching frameworks every quarter
M|prioritization-advisor|**Consequence:** Team confusion, lost time, no consistency.
M|prioritization-advisor|**Fix:** Stick with one framework for 6-12 months. Reassess only when stage/ctx changes.
M|prioritization-advisor|**Symptom:** "Feature A scored 8,000, Feature B scored 7,999, so A wins"
M|prioritization-advisor|**Consequence:** Ignores strategic ctx, judgment, and vision.
M|prioritization-advisor|**Fix:** Use frameworks as input, not automation. PM judgment overrides scores when needed.
M|prioritization-advisor|**Symptom:** PM scores features alone, presents to team
M|prioritization-advisor|**Consequence:** Lack of buy-in, engineering/design don't trust scores.
M|prioritization-advisor|**Fix:** Collaborative scoring sessions. PM, design, engineering score together.
M|prioritization-advisor|**Symptom:** "We prioritize by who shouts loudest"
M|prioritization-advisor|**Consequence:** HiPPO (Highest Paid Person's Opinion) wins, not data or str.
M|prioritization-advisor|**Fix:** Pick *any* framework. Even imperfect structure beats chaos.
M|prioritization-advisor|- `user-story.md` — Prioritized features become user stories
M|prioritization-advisor|- `epic-hypothesis.md` — Prioritized epics validated with experiments
M|prioritization-advisor|- `recommendation-canvas.md` — Business outcomes inform prioritization
M|prioritization-advisor|- Intercom, *RICE Prioritization* (2016) — Origin of RICE framework
M|prioritization-advisor|- Sean McBride, *ICE Scoring* (2012) — Lightweight prioritization
M|prioritization-advisor|- Luke Hohmann, *Innovation Games* (2006) — Buy-a-Feature and other collaborative methods
M|prioritization-advisor|- Noriaki Kano, *Kano Model* (1984) — Customer satisfaction framework
